    "summary": "The Italian Renaissance (c. 1300–1600 AD) was the epicenter of the broader [[event:96|Renaissance]] movement, originating in the wealthy city-states of northern and central Italy — Florence, Venice, Milan, Rome — where the convergence of merchant wealth, classical antiquity, and Byzantine refugee scholarship created the conditions for an extraordinary flourishing of art, literature, philosophy, and science. Florence under the [[event:2299|Medici family]] was the movement's heart, but the Italian Renaissance was a genuinely pan-Italian phenomenon encompassing the papal court at Rome, the commercial culture of Venice, and the courts of Milan and Ferrara.\n\nThe Italian Renaissance produced an unparalleled concentration of artistic genius. In painting, Giotto pioneered three-dimensional figures in the early 14th century; Masaccio introduced mathematical perspective in the 1420s; Botticelli synthesized classical mythology and Christian allegory; and [[event:2298|Leonardo da Vinci]] brought anatomical precision, atmospheric perspective, and psychological depth to a level unmatched in Western painting before or since. In sculpture, Donatello created the first free-standing nude since antiquity; [[event:3620|Michelangelo]] surpassed him with the David and the Sistine Chapel ceiling. In architecture, Brunelleschi engineered the Florence Cathedral dome — an engineering feat without precedent in medieval Europe — and rediscovered classical proportional principles. The humanist scholars Petrarch, Boccaccio, Bruni, and Pico della Mirandola reoriented intellectual culture toward human dignity, classical Latin, and critical philology.\n\nThe Italian Renaissance's export to the rest of Europe was accelerated by Italian artists and scholars traveling north, the spread of Italian printed books, and the political upheavals (French and Spanish invasions of Italy from 1494) that scattered Italian talent across Europe. By 1500, Renaissance ideas had established themselves from England to Poland, transforming European education, art, and thought.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_Renaissance",
